Let's create a new project and build our very own version of the classic command line search tool `grep` (globally search a regular expression and print). In the simplest use case, `grep` searches a specified file for a specified string. Our tool, which we'll call `minigrep`, will take a filename and a string as command line arguments.

We create a new project with `cargo new minigrep`. The first task is to make `minigrep` accept its two command line arguments: the file path and a string to search for. We want to be able to run our program with `cargo run`, two hyphens to indicate the following arguments are for our program rather than for `cargo`, a string to search for, and a path to a file:

```
$ cargo run -- searchstring example-filename.txt
```

The function provided in Rust's standard library to read command line arguments is `std::env::args`. This function returns an iterator of the command line arguments passed to the program:

```rust
use std::env;

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();
    println!("{args:?}");
}
```

First, we bring the `std::env` module into scope with a `use` statement so we can use its `args` function. The `std::env::args` function returns an iterator, and we call `collect` on it to turn it into a vector containing all the values.

Note that `std::env::args` will panic if any argument contains invalid Unicode. If your program needs to accept arguments containing invalid Unicode, use `std::env::args_os` instead.

Now let's save the values of the two arguments in variables so we can use the values throughout the rest of the program:

```rust
use std::env;

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();
    let query = &args[1];
    let file_path = &args[2];
    println!("Searching for {query}");
    println!("In file {file_path}");
}
```

